  "If you double the mass of an object while keeping the net force the same, what happens to its acceleration?": "",
  "It doubles": "",
  "It halves": "",
  "It stays the same": "",
  "It quadruples": "",
  "From F = ma, if force stays constant and mass doubles, then acceleration = F/(2m) = half the original acceleration. Acceleration is inversely proportional to mass when force is constant.": "",
  "A 10 N net force acts on a 2 kg object. What is the acceleration?": "",
  "20 m/s²": "",
  "5 m/s²": "",
  "0.2 m/s²": "",
  "12 m/s²": "",
  "Using F = ma, we solve for a = F/m = 10 N / 2 kg = 5 m/s². The acceleration is 5 meters per second squared in the direction of the net force.": "",
