  "The gravitational force pulling an object toward Earth's center": "",
  "The quantity of matter in an object, measured in kilograms": "",
  "The amount of space an object occupies in a container": "",
  "The speed at which an object moves across a surface": "",
  "In F = ma, mass (m) is the quantity of matter in an object, measured in kilograms (kg). Mass determines how much an object resists acceleration — a larger mass requires more force to achieve the same acceleration.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'weight' in physics?": "",
  "The amount of matter an object contains regardless of location": "",
  "The force of gravity acting on an object, equal to mg": "",
  "The density of an object multiplied by its total volume": "",
  "The net force that causes an object to move forward": "",
  "Weight is the force of gravity acting on an object. It is calculated as W = mg, where m is the mass and g is the gravitational acceleration. Weight is measured in Newtons and changes depending on the strength of gravity at the location.": "",
  "What does 'directly proportional' mean in the context of F = ma?": "",
  "When one quantity increases, the other decreases by the same factor": "",
  "When one quantity increases, the other increases by the same factor": "",
  "Both quantities always remain exactly equal to each other": "",
  "The two quantities have no mathematical connection at all": "",
  "In F = ma, force and acceleration are directly proportional when mass is constant. This means if you double the force, the acceleration also doubles. If you triple the force, acceleration triples. They increase together by the same factor.": "",
  "What does 'inversely proportional' mean regarding mass and acceleration?": "",
  "When mass increases, acceleration increases by the same factor": "",
  "When mass increases, acceleration decreases by the same factor": "",
  "Mass and acceleration are always equal to each other in value": "",
  "Mass and acceleration have no relationship to each other at all": "",
  "When force is constant, mass and acceleration are inversely proportional. This means doubling the mass cuts the acceleration in half. Tripling the mass reduces acceleration to one third. More mass means less acceleration for the same force.": "",
  "What does the term 'gravitational field strength' refer to?": "",
  "The force of gravity per unit mass at a given location": "",
  "The total weight of all objects within a gravitational field": "",
  "The speed at which objects fall through the atmosphere": "",
  "The distance between a planet and its closest orbiting moon": "",
  "Gravitational field strength (g) is the force of gravity per unit mass at a location, measured in N/kg (equivalent to m/s²). Near Earth's surface, g ≈ 9.8 N/kg. It varies by location — it is weaker on the Moon (~1.6 N/kg) and stronger on Jupiter (~24.8 N/kg).": "",
  "What is the definition of 'net force' in Newton's Second Law?": "",
  "The vector sum of all forces acting on an object": "",
  "The single largest force acting on an object at any time": "",
  "The force applied by a person directly pushing the object": "",
  "The gravitational pull between two objects with mass": "",
  "Net force is the vector sum of all individual forces acting on an object. In F = ma, the F refers to this net force. If forces cancel out, the net force is zero and there is no acceleration.": "",
